  "answer": "Both texts are in the corpus. Iqbal's 'Wataniyat' is Bang-E-Dara Part 3, chapter 25; the relevant Comte works are Charles Comte's Traité de la propriété Vol I (chapters 7–8) and Traité de Législation Vols II–III.\n\n**Iqbal's operative claims ('Wataniyat', allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8, ch. 25):**\n1. Territorial nationalism is the 'greatest idol' of the modern age — it 'wears Faith's own final desecration as its robe.'\n2. It lays waste to the Prophet's house of faith and Islamic unity.\n3. The state defines the nation as land; the Prophet defines homeland as divine command (umma, not territory): 'In the discourse of the state, the Nation is but land; in the Prophet's teaching, Homeland is by God's command.'\n4. Territorial nationalism sows inter-communal rivalry, drives conquest, makes politics flee from truth, and tears apart 'God's own creation.'\n5. It shears the roots of Islamic brotherhood — Muslims should be a transnational community, not bounded by soil.\n\n**Charles Comte's operative claims (charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99, chs. 7–8; charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d and vol-iii):**\n1. Each nation has a natural territorial property — the highest and most encompassing form of property (ch. 7, p-2cfb18).\n2. Natural limits (mountains, seas, rivers) determine the proper territorial boundaries of peoples; nations organized within these natural limits prosper, while artificial territorial arrangements produce strife (ch. 8, p-55b726).\n3. As a nation develops intellectually and materially, its territorial property becomes more incontestable: 'the more a nation develops... the more the territory it occupies becomes for it an incontestable and uncontested property' (ch. 7, p-0a6e26).\n4. Local territorial circumstances (soil, climate, configuration) shape the physical, intellectual, and moral development of peoples — natural territorial organization is the precondition for civilizational progress (Traité de Législation Vol III, ch. 42).\n5. Artificial territorial divisions imposed by dynastic ambition are contrary to nature and retard moral and civilizational progress; the solution is not to abandon territorial identity but to align political units with natural geographical limits.\n\n**Where the disagreement is substantive:**\n1. *The proper unit of moral community.* For Iqbal, the correct locus of collective identity is the transnational umma (faith-community defined by divine command); territorial location is irrelevant — 'To be confined to one place is calamity.' For Comte, the natural and morally productive unit is precisely the territorially bounded people. This is a genuine, deep disagreement.\n2. *The moral valence of territorial attachment.* Iqbal treats wataniyat as a form of idolatry that destroys Islamic brotherhood and drives conquest. Comte treats territorial property as a natural right and the basis of inter-national justice. They contradict each other directly on whether territorial nationalism is morally corrupting or morally foundational.\n3. *The direction of moral progress.* Iqbal implies moral progress for Muslims means transcending territorial particularity toward universal Islamic community. Comte argues moral progress follows the consolidation of territorial organization — progress moves toward better-bounded, more stable territorial nations, not beyond them.\n\n**Where it is merely vocabulary:**\n1. *'Natural.'* Both appeal to 'nature' — Iqbal to divine/natural order of the Islamic umma, Comte to physical geography. The shared term masks a real disagreement about what nature or divine command requires.\n2. *Criticism of artificial imposition.* Iqbal criticizes territorial nationalism as an alien European import ('this new age's philosophy'). Comte criticizes dynastic territorial divisions as contrary to nature. Both reject artificial arrangements — but Iqbal's deeper objection is to any territorial basis for collective identity, not just artificial ones. Comte would reform bad borders into good natural ones; Iqbal rejects the premise that territory should define collective identity at all.\n3. *'Progress.'* Both believe in civilizational improvement, but the shared word conceals incompatible content: for Comte, progress means better territorial organization; for Iqbal, return to universal Islamic brotherhood transcending territory.\n\n**Summary:** The disagreement is primarily substantive. The core dispute is whether moral solidarity properly inheres in a territorially bounded natural community (Comte) or a transnational faith community irreducible to land (Iqbal). The only area of superficial convergence — shared rejection of 'artificial' arrangements — dissolves because they disagree about what a non-artificial arrangement looks like. Note: the corpus contains only Charles Comte, not Auguste Comte.",
